{{Infobox song | name = Ellada, Hora Tou Fotos | cover = Garbi ellada chora tou fotos.jpg | alt = | type = single | artist = [[Katy Garbi|Katerina Garbi]] | album = [[Os Ton Paradeiso]] | released = 1993 | format = CD single | recorded = | studio = | venue = | genre = [[Tsifteteli|Greek Belly Dance]], [[Popular music|pop]] | length = 2:57 | label = [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music Greece]]/[[Columbia Records|Columbia]] | writer = Dimosthenis Stringlis | producer = | prev_title = | prev_year = | next_title = [[Ti Theloune Ta Matia Sou]] | next_year = 2000 | misc = {{Infobox song contest entry | embed=yes | song = {{flagicon|Greece}} "Ellada, Hora Tou Fotos" | image = | caption = | year = 1993 | country = Greece | artist = Katy Garbi | as = Katerina Garbi | with = | language = Greek | languages = | composer = Dimosthenis Stringlis | lyricist = Dimosthenis Stringlis | conductor = Charis Andreadis | place = 9th | points = 64 | lyrics = | prev = "Olou Tou Kosmou I Elpida" | prev_link = Olou Tou Kosmou I Elpida | next = "To Trehandiri" | next_link = To Trehandiri }} }} "'''Ellada, Hora Tou Fotos'''" ([[Greek alphabet|Greek]]: Ελλάδα, χώρα του φωτός, [[English language|English]]: "Greece, Country of Light") is a song by [[Greece|Greek]] pop singer [[Katy Garbi|Katerina Garbi]]. It was [[Greece]]'s entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1993]], and a single from Garbi's fifth solo album ''[[Os Ton Paradeiso]]''. Ellada, Hora Tou Fotos was the first CD single to ever be commercially released in Greece, beginning a new trend in the way Greek artists would release 1-5 tracks to the market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tovima.gr/relatedarticles/article/?aid=124792|title=Τα 45άρια των λέιζερ|publisher=''To Vima Newspaper''|accessdate=2013-05-07}}</ref>
==At Eurovision== The song was performed sixth on the night, following [[Denmark]]'s [[Tommy Seebach|Tommy Seebach Band]] with "[[Under stjernerne på himlen]]" and preceding [[Belgium]]'s [[Barbara Dex]] with "[[Iemand als jij]]". At the close of voting, it had received 64 points, placing 9th in a field of 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/index/main?page=66&event=235|title=History by Year - Eurovision Song Contest 1993|publisher=''Eurovision.tv ([[European Broadcasting Union|EBU]])''|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref> The song is in fact a praise of Greece itself, with Garbi singing about its great intellectual and cultural heritage, despite criticizing the country's inability to transform and develop and emphasizing on the great need for a change. It is thus considered partly a political and social criticism song. It was succeeded as [[Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest|Greek representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1994|1994 Contest]] by [[Costas Bigalis]] & [[The Sea Lovers]] with "[[To Trehandiri]]".
