{{Infobox postage stamp | common_name = Halfpenny Rose Red | image = [[File:British 1870 half penny plate 13 stamps.jpg|200px]] | country_of_production = [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] | location_of_production = | date_of_production = {{Start date|1870|10|01|df=y}}–{{End date|1880}} | face_value = {{frac|1|2}}d | commemorates = | depicts = [[Queen Victoria]] | notability = {{Plainlist| * First halfpenny UK stamp * Smallest UK stamp }} | designer = | engraver = | printer = | dimensions = <!-- {{convert|width|x|height|mm|in|abbr=on}} --> | perforation = | nature_of_rarity = | number_in_existence = | estimated_value = }}
The '''Halfpenny Rose Red''', first issued on 1 October 1870, was the first [[Halfpenny (British pre-decimal coin)|halfpenny]] [[postage stamp]] issued in the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].
The halfpenny stamp was introduced following a reduction in the postal rate for newspapers and postcards. It was designed to be approximately half the size of the corresponding one penny stamp and is notable for being the smallest UK postage stamp ever issued at {{cvt|17.5|x|14|mm}}.<ref name=Guinness>{{cite book|date=1 September 1988|author=James MacKay|isbn=0851123511|title=The Guinness Book of Stamps Facts & Feats|publisher=Guinness}}</ref>
The stamps (nicknamed 'Bantams' due to their small size) were printed in sheets of 480 (20 horizontal rows of 24 stamps). They were line engraved and featured a bust of [[Victoria of the United Kingdom| Queen Victoria]] in profile with '½d' on either side.
A plate number was engraved in the design, in the left and right side lace work. The plates were numbered from 1 to 20, but plates 2, 7, 16, 17, and 18 were not completed, plates 21 and 22 were not used and plate 9 is now scarce because it was a rarely used reserve plate. The stamps were watermarked with the word "halfpenny" that extended across three stamps.<ref name=Gibbons>[[Stanley Gibbons Ltd]], ''Specialised Stamp Catalogue Volume 1: Queen Victoria''</ref><ref name=pennyreds>[http://pennyreds.tripod.com/halfpenny.html Halfpenny Rose Red at ''pennyreds'']</ref>
The stamp was replaced in 1880 by the surface printed Halfpenny Green stamp.
