{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Hamilcar Barca]], the father of Hannibal.}}
'''Hamilcar''' ({{lang-xpu|𐤇𐤌𐤋𐤊}}, {{sc|ḥmlk}}){{sfnp|Huss|1985|p=[https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=NvEK7kc3qnQC&pg=PA565 565]}} was a general who succeeded to the command of the [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginians]] in the [[First Punic War]]. He defeated [[Roman Republic|Rome]]'s allies at the [[Battle of Thermae]] in 259 BC and killed 4,000–6,000 of them with the help of surprise and good use of [[military intelligence]].{{sfn|Lazenby|1996|p=73}}{{sfn|Rankov|2011|p=154}} He then captured the towns of [[Enna]] and [[Camarina]] that same year with traitors.{{sfn|Lazenby|1996|p=75}}{{sfn|Rankov|2011|p=154}} He was defeated at the [[Battle of Tyndaris]] in 257 BC, losing 18 ships and sinking 9 Roman ships. He failed to prevent the Roman landing in Africa, being defeated at the [[Battle of Ecnomus|Ecnomus]] in 256 BC, one of the largest naval battles in antiquity, with the loss of 94 ships, to the Romans' 24. After the Roman invasion of Africa, Hamilcar was recalled by Carthage from Sicily. He was defeated at the [[Battle of Adys]] in 255 BC by [[Marcus Atilius Regulus]].

