[[File:Tax ruling luxembourg.png|thumb|A leaked tax ruling signed by Marius Kohl]] '''Marius Kohl''' (born 16 September 1953)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g8fip1kplyr33r3krz5b97d1.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/SPOLITICO-16121416520.pdf|title=Medical note for Marius Kohl, excusing him from court appearance. His social security number includes his birthdate.|last=|first=|date=|work=Politico magazine|website=|publisher=|access-date=6 January 2017}}</ref> is the former chief of the [[Luxembourg]] tax agency ''Sociétés 6''.<ref name="wsj-2014">{{cite news |title=Business-friendly bureaucrat helped build tax haven in Luxembourg |website=[[Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/luxembourg-tax-deals-under-pressure-1413930593 |date=October 21, 2014 |first1=Matthew |last1=Karnitschnig |first2=Robin |last2=van Daalen }}</ref><ref name="qz-2014">{{cite news |title=Monsieur Ruling: how the tax wizard of Luxembourg made corporate burdens disappear |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |url=http://qz.com/286705/how-the-tax-wizard-of-luxembourg-made-corporate-burdens-disappear/ |date=October 24, 2014 |first=Tim |last=Fernholz }}</ref> During his 22-year tenure, he was solely responsible for approving thousands of tax arrangements for foreign companies investing capital in Luxembourg. He retired in 2013.{{r|wsj-2014}} Kohl was known by the nickname "Monsieur Ruling" and has been credited with helping to secure €1.2 billion in annual tax revenue for Luxembourg.{{r|qz-2014}}
==Luxembourg Leaks== {{Main|Luxembourg Leaks}}
The [[Advance tax ruling|tax rulings]] released in the [[Luxembourg Leaks]] were sought by [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] and approved by Kohl.
